In mathematics, a '''Segal space''' is a [[simplicial space]] satisfying some [[pullback]] conditions, making it look like a [[Homotopy|homotopical]] version of a [[Category (mathematics)|category]]. More precisely, a [[simplicial set]], considered as a simplicial discrete space, satisfies the Segal conditions iff it is the [[Nerve (category theory)|nerve]] of a category. The condition for Segal spaces is a homotopical version of this. 

Complete Segal spaces were introduced by {{harvtxt|Rezk|2001}} as models for [[(infinity,1)-category|(∞,&nbsp;1)-categories]].

